{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569727"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:31:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:31:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22313"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22313"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.19,0.07,0.19,0.42]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15278"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108900"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15278"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22313"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91267"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40519"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40520"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43772"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47516"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108900"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine review of her chronic kidney disease. She has stage 3b chronic kidney disease with an estimated glomerular filtration rate of 35 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (60-90). Her medical history includes type 2 diabetes, hypertension, and dyslipidaemia. Her current medications include metformin, perindopril, hydrochlorothiazide, rosuvastatin, and empagliflozin. She does not smoke and drinks alcohol occasionally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. You decide to discuss a sick day action plan, which includes medications to stop during illnesses to prevent acute kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications can be continued as part of the plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Metformin","Perindopril","Hydrochlorothiazide","Empagliflozin","Rosuvastatin"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESick day action plans are an important preventive strategy for patients with chronic kidney disease to reduce the risk of acute kidney injury during periods of acute illness. The SADMANS mnemonic helps identify medications that should be temporarily withheld during acute illness, especially when patients are at risk of dehydration or hypotension.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERosuvastatin\u003C/strong\u003E is a statin used for cholesterol management and cardiovascular risk reduction. Statins do not significantly affect kidney haemodynamics or increase the risk of acute kidney injury during periods of dehydration. Therefore, they can generally be continued during sick days and are not included in the SADMANS mnemonic.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetformin\u003C/strong\u003E is represented by the \u0027M\u0027 in SADMANS. During acute illness, especially with dehydration, there is an increased risk of lactic acidosis with metformin use in patients with reduced kidney function. Therefore, metformin should be temporarily withheld during acute illness.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerindopril\u003C/strong\u003E is an angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor, represented by the \u0027A\u0027 in SADMANS. These medications can impair the kidney\u0027s ability to maintain glomerular filtration during periods of reduced renal perfusion by blocking the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system. This can potentially worsen kidney function during dehydration or hypotension.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydrochlorothiazide\u003C/strong\u003E is a thiazide diuretic, represented by the \u0027D\u0027 in SADMANS. Diuretics can exacerbate volume depletion during periods of illness with poor oral intake or fluid losses, potentially worsening dehydration and increasing the risk of acute kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmpagliflozin\u003C/strong\u003E is an SGLT2 inhibitor, represented by the \u0027S\u0027 in SADMANS. These medications increase the risk of dehydration and ketoacidosis during periods of acute illness. They can also impair the kidney\u0027s ability to concentrate urine, potentially worsening volume depletion and increasing the risk of acute kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Medications in the SADMANS mnemonic (Sulfonylureas, ACE inhibitors, Diuretics, Metformin, ARBs, NSAIDs, SGLT2 inhibitors) should be temporarily discontinued during acute illness in patients with chronic kidney disease.","Sick day action plans help prevent acute kidney injury during periods of illness when patients may be at risk of dehydration or hypotension.","Statins can generally be continued during acute illness as they do not significantly impact kidney function during periods of dehydration."],"references":["Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) Management in Primary Care (5th edition). Kidney Health Australia. 2024. Available from:\u00a0https://assets.kidney.org.au/resources/KHA-CKD-Handbook-5th-Ed-July2024.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91267"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22313"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91267"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-14T18:31:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-14T18:34:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15278"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108900"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https:/